Those who smoke have a higher risk of losing teeth.
Smoking does not only damage the lungs, but also the teeth – a long-term Potsdam study suggests.
The good news is that if you give up, the risk drops quickly.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is evident from the long-term study of an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutrition Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
Compared to non-smokers, smokers were at risk of losing their teeth prematurely by 2.5 to 3.6 times higher.
The scientists had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth loss are tooth decay and inflammation of the gums, the DIFE emphasizes.
For this periodontitis, smoking is a risk factor, the authors stress.
The link between smoking and tooth loss is therefore due to more frequent gum inflammation in smokers.
It is not clear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of caries.
People who quit smoking, however, could reduce their risk within a short time, the researchers write in the "Journal of Dental Research".
However, it could take more than ten years for the threat to return to the level of non-smokers, said lead author Thomas Dietrich of the University of Birmingham.
One must convince people to become non-smokers, study leader Heiner Boeing of the DIFE stated: "Smoking shortens life."
Not smoking is good for lungs and vessels and, according to our findings, also leads to good dental health up to old age.
In Germany, more than 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 years are affected by toothlessness, the DIFE said.
Previous studies have already indicated that smoking increases the risk of early tooth loss.
The new long-term study underpins the findings.
