Metcash launches ground resistance campaign to combat Aldi incident
Metcash is trying to protect the IGA branches from an Aldi advance in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a grounding campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
As Aldi prepares to open two distribution centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets strengthen their relationships with local food suppliers and build the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and social media marketing, as well as events such as Adelaide show.
IGA dealers and suppliers jump on board, with brands such as ice cream maker Simmo from Dunsborough, who distribute samples in IGA stores and shop owners selling discounted tickets for the South Australian Football League to loyal customers.
It is expected that Metcash will release further details of its defense strategy on September 29, when the food, alcohol, and equipment wholesaler will execute its annual investor strategy day.
There is a lot at stake as South Australia and Western Australia account for nearly 30 percent of Metcash’s IGA retail stores and generate higher profit margins than Metcash’s IGA network in the Eastern states.
Buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland – more than 30 percent in South Australia and 24 percent in Western Australia compared to around 14 percent in the Eastern states.
However, analysts like Morgan Stanley believe that twelve months after opening its first markets, Aldi will snatch away about five percent of the food market in these two states and will take away all existing players, but mainly independent retailers, sales.
According to a report released this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in revenue per year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 branches in SA and 30 in WA next year, generating sales of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and food business and in the amounts on Metcash’s high fixed-cost basis could cost Metcash around $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the Eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley estimates that Metcash’s revenue in the food and food business will fall by 3.8 percent in 2016, by 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018 and will reduce its market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, leading fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of the Magellan Financial Group, told a business dinner in Melbourne that Metcash is likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash refused to respond publicly to Mr Douglass’ comments.
But it is assumed that a Metcash board member contacted Mr Douglass last week.
IGA’s market share has fallen from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and revenues from Metcash’s food and food trade, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers, have fallen by 43 percent since 2012, reflecting operational debt reductions while simultaneously pushing sales and margins.
However, the wholesaler is resisting and investing more than $150 million to match sales prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products each week and improve IGA retailers in improving their stores through fast-growing fresh foods and delivering a better choice of private label foods.
Metcash’s chief executive, Ian Morrice, says price adjustments and shop remediation programs will increase to Elan and hopes that the wholesaler will return to profit growth for the first time in four years in 2017.
Thanasi Kokkinakis is supported by Steve Healy, President of the Australian Tennis Association
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his behavior.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damage" in the recent storm around his friend Nick Kyrgios and, according to the president of the Australian tennis association Steve Healy, deserves praise rather than criticism for his own behavior.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo, repeatedly referred to as "Special Ks", came to the limelight by the infamous confrontation of Kyrgios with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying game in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, with Harrison shouting, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should have beaten the child."
While he was last seen beating a tennis racket after a cramp thwarted a potential U.S. open win by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was steadfastly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in singles behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against the UK.
"One thing I'm pretty mature about is the fact that, in my opinion, Thanasi was a little drawn into the dispute," Healy said.
He broke a bat when he lost to the U.S. Open because of a cramp, but he's not the first player to break a bat from frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he's not proud of it.
But, really, he has behaved extremely well in the U.S. Open, even under the rather provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of recognition.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him, and I think he has been treated a little too harshly.
He is a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard, and he fits into the team and so on, he has never had a problem with the other players, he is respected in the dressing area, he is training hard, he is well in shape, he is a very stable and mature young guy, and I think he deserves to be judged according to his own merits.
Healy also supported the decision not to take Kyrgios into account in the important preliminary decision that begins on Friday, and he describes the "joint decision" as the right one for everyone, but he assures the man from Canberra to return to the team as a long-term fixed component."
“First, we want the team to be completely focused on the competition and not on all the controversy around [Kyrgios],” Healy said.
And I think Nick has very quickly made the ascent that people like Federer and Murray have pointed out. He rises in the eyes of the public, and he has made some terrible mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we try to support him, we try to make him understand the consequences of his actions. Some time out of the limelight he can only think about it, and I think it's best for him.
Europe's refugee crisis: Hungary declares emergency, closes the border, holds back refugees
Hungary declared a state of emergency and cleared the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday, holding all those who tried to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos followed at the border when hundreds of migrants gathered in a no-man’s land and Serbian officials reacted with outrage.
The people who had fled from violence were stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries and built tents and settled there.
But frustrations increased.
When a police helicopter hovered over them, the migrants chanted "Open the border!" and shouted insults against the Hungarian readiness police.
Some rejected food and water from protest.
Serbia’s foreign minister said it was “unacceptable” that migrants would be sent back from Hungary, while more and more from Macedonia and Greece arrived.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not a collateral damage.
There must be talks with Brussels and other countries in the coming days," said Ivica Dacic in Prague.
The turbulence on the Hungarian-Serbian border came one day after the 28-nation bloc failed to agree a common immigration policy at a controversial meeting in Brussels.
However, the ministers agreed to share responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in the crowded Italy and Greece, expressing their hope that eventually - next month or by the end of the year - an agreement would be reached that EU states would take in another 120,000 refugees, including some from Hungary.
Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria called for a special summit of the European Union on Tuesday to discuss the continent’s immigration crisis.
Hungary, however, did not rely on an early action by Brussels or its neighbours.
The state of emergency in two southern regions on Tuesday gave authorities more power to cope with the crisis, allowing them to lock down roads and speed up asylum procedures.
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto said his country was also planning to build a barbed wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country – after it ended a fence on the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even prison inmates were employed in the race to create the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a major bottleneck for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East and a point of entry into the European Union.
However, Prime Minister Viktor Orban has insisted that most arriving are economic refugees who are looking for a better life, and not war refugees who are entitled to protection – a view that is strongly opposed to other EU countries, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make crossing the border or damaging the 4-meter (13-foot) high fence that the government had built along the southern border with Serbia a crime, which also imposes higher prison sentences for convicted traffickers.
"Due to the situation caused by mass migration, the Hungarian government explains the state of emergency," Zoltan Kovacs, a government spokesman, told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: Illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament still has to agree to the use of the military, which is expected for next week, but Associated Press reporters have seen heavily armed soldiers carrying vehicles and dogs on the border for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, the state security adviser for Orban, said authorities seized 45 people while trying to cross the border, 15 others had already penetrated deeper into the country.
They come over by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
Authorities are in the process of repairing the fence quickly.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a train wagon with barbed wire to close the borders had arrived.
Chaos surrounded the most important border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when the Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process the data of people and pushed a crowd to push themselves in there.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands remained outside.
Another group of migrants blocked Serbia’s and Hungary’s main highway connection and said they would refuse food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
2016 election: Hillary Clinton's lead ahead of Bernie Sanders halved in national poll
Former U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton continues to hold a double-digit lead in the Democratic race for the nomination at national level, but Senator Bernie Sanders wins against her on the ground.
Clinton now has the support of 47 percent of Democratic voters in the primaries (58 percent before), while Sanders is in second place, with 27 percent (up 17 percent).
Vice President Joe Biden, who has not yet announced whether he will run for president, will receive support from 15 percent of the Democratic voters in the primaries.
More than five months before the start of the primaries, most Democratic voters say it’s too early to say that their opinion is fixed on which candidates they will support.
But Clinton’s supporters are more consistent in their choice than the other candidates.
Since the CBS News poll, Clinton has lost to a number of demographic groups, while Sanders made some profits.
Clinton holds a big lead in women and moderates, but these advances have decreased.
Their support for the men has dropped significantly, and Sanders is only down with 5 points.
Clinton’s advantage to Democratic voters under 50 has eluded, and she and Sanders are now on the same level.
However, Clinton still has a big advantage among the older voters.
Last month, Clinton was ahead of Sanders with a double-digit lead in the Liberals, but Sanders now has a 5-point lead in this group.
About half of the Democratic voters nationwide say they would be enthusiastically supporting Clinton if she were nominated by the party.
A quarter would support her with some reservations and another 15 percent would only support her because she is the candidate.
Six percent would not support them.
Perhaps not surprisingly, Clinton’s current supporters are especially excited about her.
The views are more mixed among those who currently do not support Clinton – only about a quarter would support her enthusiastically.
While 48 percent of Democratic voters in the primaries say they support Clinton with enthusiasm, fewer Republican voters say so about their top candidate Donald Trump (35 percent).
When Clinton’s supporters are asked in an open question why they want her to be the candidate, the most common answer is that she has the right experience (16 percent), followed by the view that it’s time for a woman to become president (13 percent) and that she’s the best candidate for the job (10 percent).
Clinton’s supporters also mention their connection with Bill Clinton (9%).
Consent to deal with the problems and selectability are also cited.
As the vice president throws a potential for the presidential office into the balance, 57 percent of the Democratic voters of the primaries want to see him in the race — even though a third believe he shouldn’t.
When Democratic voters are asked who would be their second choice for the party, Biden is at the top.
More than half of Clinton’s supporters say Biden would be their second choice far ahead of Sanders.
If Biden decides not to run for the Democratic nomination, Hillary Clinton's lead against Sanders will increase from 20 points with Biden in the race to 30 points without him in the race.
Fifty-five percent of Democratic voters see Clinton as a candidate with the best chances of winning the election; however, that number dropped by 78 percent last month.
Biden is by far a second at this measurement, but the percentage that sees him as the "most selectable" has risen.
However, when asked what is more important for a candidate, Democratic voters ask questions about the selectivity.
Similar to last month, no single Democratic candidate or potential candidate for these voters in the primaries stands out as unacceptable.
The Democratic candidates or potential candidates produce good results on some important features among voters of their party’s pre-elections.
Majorities consider Clinton, Sanders and Biden to be honest and trustworthy and endowed with strong leadership qualities.
Biden is best off with the three candidates on honesty, while Clinton’s strength is the lead.
Thirty percent of Democratic voters don’t believe Clinton is honest and trustworthy, twice as many say that about Sanders (15 percent), but 27 percent don’t agree with him.
Democratic voters of the primaries generally also see Clinton, Sanders and Biden ideologically in line with their views.
In all of these measurements, about a quarter of Democratic voters have no opinion of Sanders.
As questions about Hillary Clinton’s use of a personal email address and a server continue to be asked during her tenure as Secretary of State, most Democratic voters of the primaries are satisfied with their statement of the matter and say that it has not affected their opinions overall.
But it is another story in the American public as a whole.
Half of Americans are now dissatisfied with their statement, while only about a third are satisfied.
The public opinion on this was divided in March, shortly after the problem came to light.
Most Americans said the email controversy had no impact on Clinton’s general opinions, although 36 percent said their opinion of hers had worsened.
It’s mostly Republicans, more than six out of 10, who say their views of Clinton have gotten worse.
Although Clinton is considered honest and trustworthy by her party’s voters, this continues to be a problem for her among registered voters overall: only 32 percent see them as honest and trustworthy, eight percent less than last month, and 15 points less since May.
62 percent of voters do not consider them an honest and trustworthy person.
At the same time, 55 percent of voters across the country also view Trump as not honest and not trustworthy.
However, Clinton and Trump get good marks on leadership.
Of the six candidates tested, Biden, Carson and Bush cut best in honesty.
A majority see Sanders rather than honest, but as with Carson, many have no opinion of him.
The error rate for the sample of 351 Democratic voters in the primary elections is 6 percentage points.
