Five members of the Brotherhood charged with the death of a Baruch college novice
Almost two years after a student died during a shady ritual of a student connection in Pocono Mountains, Pennsylvania, murder charges against five people are filed.
Members of the New York Baruch College Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood brutally attacked Chun "Michael" Deng during an introductory ritual in September 2013 and delayed his transportation to the hospital, which contributed to his death, police said.
Officials said he had been charged with blindfolded eyes with a 30-pound backpack full of sand, and repeatedly attacked while trying to reach a target via a frozen field.
Mr. Deng eventually complained about headaches, then he fell unconscious.
The members of the Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood did not call 911 after Deng fainted and allegedly waited an hour before bringing him to a hospital, police said.
However, they had the time to change Deng’s clothes, Google his symptoms, and contact Andy Meng, the national president of the Brotherhood, to seek advice, police chief Chris Wagner said at a press conference.
"At this point, the members began to hide utensils and basically put the welfare of the Brotherhood above that of Michael Deng," said police chief Wagner.
He could not be revived, and he died the next morning from his injuries.
According to an autopsy report, Deng was repeatedly inflicted with blunt force injuries to the head, trunk and thighs.
“Too many families were destroyed by the harassment of the Brotherhood, at least one student has died every year since 1970,” said Douglas Fierberg, a lawyer representing Deng’s family.
Brotherhoods and their members must be held accountable, and this step by authorities is very important.
A Monroe County Grand Jury recommended a third-degree murder charge for the first five members.
Thirty-two members of the Brotherhood, including Mr Meng, are also charged with harassment and the formation of a criminal association.
“We don’t just want to hold the people involved accountable, but if there’s an organization that has sanctioned this – officially or unofficially – we’re going to hold them accountable,” Wagner said at a press conference on Tuesday.
Baruch College has banned the Brotherhood, and the National Brotherhood has revoked its membership of the local group.
This will happen when the Fed increases interest rates
An increase in interest rates will come, and the house will shake, yields for bonds will rise, and the economy will slide into a recession.
We know that.
What we don’t know is how long it will take and how long it will last.
In particular, the history of the economy offers little guidance on the course of events.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first interest rate increase and lasted 86 months.
The aggressiveness of the Federal Reserve in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial investments react.
Therefore, representatives of the U.S. central bank have stressed so strongly that investors should not focus on when it starts to raise interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
However, in the end, market participants might find that the whole excitement may have been exaggerated due to an increase in interest rates.
“The first increase in the Fed since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the era of ‘cheap money’,” Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a statement to customers.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal levels, but still to low levels to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no impact.
Here’s a look at how some areas of the economy might react based on historical trends:
As the market has seen in the past month, the anticipation of interest rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
As soon as the increase occurs, the impact is not so dramatic.
"There seems to be a tendency for asset yields to be slashed 12 to 24 months after the first increase, which may reflect the delay in monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after Fed interest rate hikes.
More specifically, the market has mostly been on the upward trend in the past 35 years – about 14 percent – on its way to interest rate hike, fairly flat in the 250 days following (average profit of 2.6 percent), then back to normal state after 500 days, with an average return in the past six past cycles of 14.4 percent, according to a current analysis published by Bob Doll, chief investment strategist at Nuve Baren.
Deutsche Bank said that the impact on the shares tends to occur later in the increase cycle and the return begins to decrease.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate increases often promote them.
In the current case, the Fed is faced with some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
It is extremely remarkable here that the gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point in an interest rate hike by the Fed.
According to Deutsche Bank, at the 118 interest rate hikes since 1950, nominal GDP was only twice below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect this to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest rate hikes in such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky and raise the question of “whether it’s different this time around,” Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been gearing up for a Fed interest rate hike all year round, and all eyes were on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week ending Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading only indicates a 25 percent probability.
“In our study, all cycles of increase from 1950 to the present have taken place in a super cycle with increasing momentum in GDP, and pre-recession elevations have taken place very quickly after the start of recovery,” the report said.
In contrast, this is a clearly slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest that the Fed has been waiting for since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and so far this is 74 months.
Fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an interest rate increase, and the pattern is quite similar to that of the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic price.
In the case of bonds, returns seem to change direction as soon as the first increase/lower occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields fall immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
The strategists of Charles Schwab believe that the rise in interest rates will cause yields between longer and shorter bonds to converge closer and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-yield bonds often bring better yields in such a climate, although “we are still careful to expect higher yields,” Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones says that the markets have already adapted to Fed strategy expectations.
“In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy,” she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have increased, the yield curve is flatter, loan margins have expanded and volatility has increased – all features of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
By and large, companies that do most of their business in the U.S. will benefit from this as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational companies with high debt will be worse off, as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market and also financing their debt.
"The story shows that "quality" stocks tend to respond very positively three months after an initial interest rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for customers.
Firms with a strong balance sheet have, on average, exceeded 5 percentage points after each of the 1994, 1999 and 2004 interest rate hikes.
Companies with high capital returns and low volatility in their shares also outperformed their low-quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) respectively.
Debt is going to be a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of the pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see gains from higher returns, even if experts disagree on how quickly this will take place.
