Experts Criticize Public Health England Report on E-Cigarettes
Claims by a government-funded agency that e-cigarettes are less harmful than smoking originated from a meeting of 12 people, partly with links to the tobacco industry, researchers said.
Experts writing in the British Medical Journal (BMJ) joined Lancet by criticizing the evidence used by Public Health England (PHE) in their report on e-cigarettes.
PHE published the "principal report" last month and described it as a "comprehensive review of the evidence".
However, some researchers have questioned the resilience of the data and pointed out the links between some experts and the tobacco industry.
An editorial in the medical journal Lancet last month attacked the "extraordinarily windy basis" on which PHE justified its main conclusion.
Two other researchers write in BMJ and have asked if the claims “build on stone or sand”.
Martin McKee, Professor of European Public Health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine and Simon Capewell, Professor of Clinical Epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, said: "A fundamental principle of public health is that strategies should be based on evidence of effectiveness."
They said the public expects PHE’s claim that “the current best estimate is that e-cigarettes are about 95% less harmful than smoking” is based on a detailed review of the evidence and modeling.
In fact, this statement comes from a single session of 12 people called to develop a model for a multi-criteria decision analysis (MCDA) to lead their opinions on the damage of various nicotine-containing products to a synthesis; the results of the meeting were summarized in a research report.
McKee and Capewell said a sponsor of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose managing director previously received British American Tobacco funds (BAT) for an independent study.
He also signed BAT’s references to public health in a sustainability report, they said.
One of the 12 participants in the meeting stated that they would receive funds from an e-cigarette manufacturer, but not the funding he was expected to receive from tobacco company Philip Morris International, according to reports.
The reasons for selecting the members of the board are not provided, but include several well-known e-cigarette champions, some of which also state industry funding in the paper.
Some other participants in this session are not known for their know-how in tobacco control.
The meeting also included the tobacco management of PHE.
The group's research work "significantly states" that there is a lack of "hard evidence for the damage of most products on most criteria," McKee and Capewell wrote.
However, none of these compounds or restrictions are discussed in the PHE report.
McKee and Capewell said PHE's claims that "there is no evidence so far that e-cigarettes serve as a way to smoke for children or non-smokers" were premature.
Prof Kevin Fenton, Director of Health and Well-Being at PHE, said that BMJ’s claims had been previously responded to.
He said, “E-cigarettes are far less harmful than smoking.”
One in two smokers died of addiction.
All the evidence suggests that the health risks of e-cigarettes are low compared to that, but that we continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has a clear duty to inform the public about what evidence proves and what does not, especially when there is so much public confusion about the relative dangers compared to tobacco.
Nearly 80,000 people die annually from a disease related to smoking, and smoking costs the National Health System <0xC2><0xA3>2 billion a year.
By clearly presenting current evidence that e-cigarettes are not risk-free, but represent only a fraction of the damage caused by smoking, we meet our national responsibilities.
