At their most anticipated meeting in the year, Federal Reserve Strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras-Mahagoni table to decide if it’s time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in almost a decade.
Threatening over them at one end of the decorated, two-storey meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the nation’s economic interests first and foremost.
The central bank has a twofold mandate from Congress: maximizing U.S. employment and keeping prices stable here.
But since the great recession, the Fed leaders have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third mandate could be the X factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict, and it will be announced on Thursday whether the US economy is ready to be weaned off the unprecedented incentive by the near-zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Although most of the data from the economy shows that it is growing solidly, recent turbulence in global financial markets could make the already cautious Fed representatives fearful of increasing this volatility by raising the interest rate on federal bonds — and even by only a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing they observe,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to continue to wait," she said.
There is no consensus as to what the Fed will do, which in itself insures the financial market.
About half of economists surveyed by Bloomberg recently predicted an interest rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to wait, with a key indicator indicating only a 30% chance of an increase.
This indicates a decline in the stock market if the Fed increases the rate unless the strategists mitigate the blow by promising that another increase is far away.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial average jumped by 228.89 points or by 1.4% to 16,599.85.
The action was triggered by expectations that Fed policies will maintain the rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed would raise the rates at that time," he said.
If she does, "they must go very far in their statement to calm the financial markets so that they don't panic."
Other experts argued that an interest rate hike would calm the financial markets because it would eliminate the uncertainty about when the Fed will trade.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed well on its way to increasing the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of recovery in the U.S.
Yellen had said in spring and early summer that despite Liberals’ complaints that more economic progress would be needed, she expects an increase in the rate this year.
Although job creation slowed down in August, the improvement in the labour market this year was solid.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest for more than seven years, and close to the level the Fed sees as full employment.
Wage increases have shown signs of recovery.
And while inflation was consistently below the central bank’s 2% annual target, Fed representatives said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy “can handle higher interest rates and needs them because of the strain on the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world were collapsing at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial average dropped by more than 16% in May when investors feared that slowing the Chinese economy would slow global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, with the Dow now being almost 10% below the May high.
For the Fed representatives, market turbulence affects the complex calculation of when to increase interest rates.
“If events in the financial markets and news about the weakness of the Chinese economy hadn’t occurred in the last few weeks, they would be pulling in the reins at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former U.S. Federal Reserve official.
Now he predicts that she will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There’s a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there’s almost no reliable data describing developments in China,” Oliner said.
The health of the world economy is not one of the main concerns of the Fed, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
The influence of the central bank has been enormous in recent years.
The mere mention by the then head Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could "restrict" its monetary expansion caused confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives can be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of the global asset management strategy of Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA., remarked this month that "the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements that are apparently unrelated to economic fundamentals."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, which advocates for an interest rate increase, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to lower its lead rate by 0.75 percentage points in three sessions “despite limited discernible impact on growth in the United States,” Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed representatives reversed these cuts.
The Fed should put aspects of financial stability first only during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market collapse, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate fixing committee.
The recent turbulences do not come close to this level, he said.
“She certainly doesn’t want to get into the situation where she’s afraid of an interest rate hike because the markets are upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains the double mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I do not think it should precede time.
