Fourfold increase in children’s use of hand sanitizer in the last 4 years
Toxic control centers in the U.S. report an almost 400 percent increase in the number of children under the age of twelve who swallow heavily alcoholic hand sanitizers, according to the Georgia Poison Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Center, cases of revenue from hand sanitizers in children under the age of 12 who report poison control centers increased from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
“Children are increasingly coming to these products, and unfortunately, a percentage of them are going into the emergency room,” Lopez told CNN.
He said that some children intentionally drink disinfectants, while some do so to impress their friends or because of a test of courage on social media.
Videos on YouTube show how teenagers drink disinfectants only because of a cheap experience.
Young people have allegedly mixed disinfectants with alcoholic mouthwash to obtain a harder drink.
Younger children can be attracted by attractive scents of disinfectants.
“A child doesn’t think this is bad for it,” Lopez said.
Many of the more attractive (hand sanitizers) are those that are perfumed.
There are disinfectants with strawberry, grape and orange scents that are very appealing for children.
Hand sanitizers contain anywhere between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in young children, a few syringes can lead to alcohol poisoning.
"It's highly concentrated alcohol," Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the poison emergency call center at the University of Kansas hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansa City.
So, you wouldn’t let a sip of whiskey stand around, but people leave these hand sanitizers within reach of children, and when children come to it, then it’s a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who had recently taken four syringes of strawberry-scented hand sanitizer in school, was taken to an emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol concentration was 179, twice higher than the threshold considered legally drunk in an adult, said Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room doctor who treated her at the Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah lashed her words and was unable to leave when she arrived in the emergency room.
Doctors monitored them overnight in a separate children's hospital for signs of brain trauma, as the girl had fallen through the alcohol and bumped her head, Ritchey said.
“That was very scary,” said Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah’s mother, CNN.
It could have been fatal for my child.
Lopez has recommended parents and teachers to use non-alcoholic products or disinfectants and store hand sanitizers outside the child’s reach.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants were associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand sanitizers containing a toxic, undeclared ingredient.
Health officials suspect that the product contained methanol, a lethal solution, rather than ethyl alcohol, which was listed as an active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-grade students in New York City planned to poison their “common” teacher by explaining antibacterial products around the classroom,” a police report said.
