The European Commission wants to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish, thus suggesting a significantly higher dose of nerve poison to consumers.
The consumer organization Foodwatch, which has a corresponding EU working paper, strongly criticized the plans: "Risks and side effects of misguided industrial and environmental policies are being passed on to pregnant women and young children with full force," explained Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limits of the nerve poison for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, are to be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons."
However, large predatory fish are already so heavily burdened with mercury that, on the basis of the limits still in force, about 50 percent of catches are not allowed to be sold.
After doubling the limit values, only 14.5 percent would be unsaleable.
In return for this easing, according to Foodwatch, the EU wants to tighten the limits for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
Foodwatch, however, called this a “trick” because smaller Friedfish, such as Carp, are usually so low that they already meet the planned peaks today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore “a perfidious distraction maneuver that helps the economy alone,” Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a heavy metal that is highly toxic to humans, which is highly enriched by the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The federal government therefore warns that “already small amounts, especially in the case of unborn babies, can cause damage to the nervous system.”
However, the Federal Ministry of the Environment declares on its homepage with regard to the current maximum levels that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury comes into the environment mainly through the burning of coal.
According to a written statement by the Federal Ministry of the Environment, the German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tonnes of mercury a year to the Greens-Bundestag MP Annalena Baerbock, two thirds of the total quantity emitted in Germany.
The concentration of mercury in fish, for example, in the Elbe, Rhine and Danube, was "permanently and extensively exceeded," the "mirror" quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings of mercury in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU warning system RASFF.
